Scientists have long believed that giraffes are mostly silent and communicate only visually with one another. But biologist Angela St&ouml;ger and her team analyzed hundreds of hours of recordings of giraffes in three European zoos and found that giraffes make a very low-pitched humming sound. The researchers claim that the giraffes use these sounds to communicate when it's not possible for them to signal one another visually.
