According to Indian economist and sociologist Radhakamal Mukerjee (1889&ndash;1968), the Eurocentric concepts that informed early twentieth-century social scientific methods—for example, the idea that all social relations are reducible to struggles between individuals—had little relevance for India. Making the social sciences more responsive to Indians' needs, Mukerjee argued, required constructing analytical categories informed by India's cultural and ecological circumstances. Mukerjee thus proposed the communalist 'Indian village&rdquo; as the ideal model on which to base Indian economic and social policy.
